node.text: Sam, Golden Retriever (16 y/o), Upper West Side, New York, NY • We’ve partnered with @thefarmersdog to tell the story of Sam, a senior rescue dog who’s living a long, fulfilling and healthy life. The Farmer’s Dog is helping senior dogs in shelters find homes in time for the holidays – follow the link at the end of the video to see adoptable seniors in shelters all across the country so hopefully you can find a Sam, too.

node.text: Oliver, German Shorthaired Pointer (11 m/o), Woods Hole Ferry, MA • “He’s a singleton (in his litter), which is rare. He runs five miles every morning. He puts everything in his mouth and suckles his blanket every night to fall asleep.”

node.text: Guinness & Melissa, Schnauzer shop dog & founder of @luckydogsurf, Sea Bright, NJ • “I dabbled in lots of other careers – I tried to be on Broadway, I tried voiceover for cartoons. It wasn’t making me happy, so I moved out to Hawaii to teach and surf – I’ve always been really passionate about surfing. I missed my family so I came back, but I couldn't get an interview in New Jersey at any school. I was substitute teaching and pretty miserable. Surfing was the only thing that made me happy. I was so depressed I couldn’t even ask for help, but my mom signed me up for therapy. I told the therapist I wanted to open a surf shop. She said, ‘Do it!’ There aren’t a lot of women owned surf shops – I knew I could start something that was less intimidating and bro-ey. We opened and started a surf camp, too, with lessons every day. I named it after my dog I grew up with, Lucky, a miniature Poodle that lived to 17. After I got my bank loan, I thought, ‘I need a shop dog.’ I went to the SPCA five minutes after they opened and saw Guinness. The one woman who was looking at him hesitated and I was like, ‘I’ll take him!’. People come into the store to see Guinness. If he’s not there people are very disappointed. We do fundraisers for the SPCA and the Humane Society. In 2019 I got hurt on my board. My board popped up and got caught in a gust of wind. The fin hit my face above my eye. It hit me so hard that it severed my optic nerve. I went blind pretty much right away in my one eye. I had a serious concussion and broke my face. I’m lucky I didn’t drown – somebody saved me. Two months later I was back on the board with modifications. I now wear a helmet and goggles (I was just paddling around today). Surfing still makes me happy. I didn’t want that one incident to ruin the life I made for myself. I’m so happy doing this. I had so many shitty bosses over my life. I knew what not to do. Every employee comes back every year. Everyone’s really happy. I’m proud of that.”

He’s a dream dog. He’s brought so much joy to our apartment. We named him Panko because I accidentally ordered 20 lbs of panko crumbs from Baldor around when we got him. His middle name is Messi – my son is a big soccer fan.”
